9751|SR21107195|OPEN|"""Constituent Affairs Inquiry"""|"""CITYCONI"""|"""

Good morning City Council Persons. My name is Anthony Loth.  I am a Senior Chief Engineer for Cushman and Wakefield. We manage properties for property owners all over the Greater Cincinnati Area. I am having a Homeless problem at one of the properties we manage at 644 Linn St  on the west side of Cincinnati. We have contacted the Cincinnati Police Dept. about this problem. We have had multiple phone calls with police officers for one on one communications about this issue. We also signed a document to allow the Cincinnati Police to represent us to keep them from trespassing on our property when they see them. However this is not being done. Our tenants don’t feel safe. Our maintenance guys and security staff are being threatened with violence. Some of them are laying in the parking lot entrances restricting our tenants from parking in the parking lot. They are drinking alcohol and using drugs, we pick needles up all the time. And not to mention the piles of garbage and poop that we have to pick up on a daily basis.

We call the police and sometimes they show up, more often they don’t. Then when they do show up they don’t do anything at all or they moved them down the road which in return they show back up 30-60 minutes later. Total disregard of the police, our property they are trespassing on, and threating our staff with bodily harm. Can you give me some direction on how to handle this or who I should contact to help resolve this issue?? I feel this is my last result before we get the media involved because we don’t know what else to do, however something has to be done. Everyone at the property is scared and this is not a good image for our city as well.
Anything you can do to help us with this matter would be greatly appreciated. Thank you and Happy Holidays.
Anthony Loth
Senior Chief Engineer
anthony.loth@cushwake.com
4680 Parkway Dr Suite 115

9888|SR21107396|NEW|"""Constituent Affairs Inquiry"""|"""CITYCONI"""|"""Communication from Tim Jeckering, President of the Northside Business Association-  forwarded to CM Mann after not receiving a response from Mayor's office.
Mayor Cranley,
I am writing this short note with the hopes you will be able to assist the Northside Business Association with an issue that somehow got way bigger than it ever should have.

In brief, NBA (under previous leadership) purchased 4024 Hamilton Ave. 45223 (titled under 4025 Hamilton LLC) in November of 2017 as a means of improving the Historic Business District.  It was clearly one of the more deteriorated buildings within the business district, the owner of the building at that time had did nothing since he owned it and the previous owners did very little over the years.  See photos in TJ-6-12-19 attached below.

I took over the presidency of NBA in January of 2019.  NBA's intention was to get the building structurally stabilized and transferred into the hands of a reputable developer.  Within 6 months of purchasing it, NBA received a citation from the City's Buildings and Inspections for the many obvious building deficiencies that had existed for decades.  I found a copy of the City’s letter laying in on the sidewalk one day when I was there to check on the building.  I immediately took action, contacted the inspector, but at that time the work orders has been issued over a year previous.

I prepared a set of construction documents within months of meeting the inspector, however, our liaison in Economic Development left for 4 months for a well deserved paternity leave, and it was not until November of 2019 that we had a contractor on board to make the stabilization repairs.  It was not the NBA's fault a City employee took a paternity leave and delayed us from bidding out the repairs.  I attended a hearing after the repairs were completed but was unsuccessful in pleading our case.  NBA sold the building to Northside’s NEST earlier this year.  NEST is preparing construction documents on the entire building for redevelopment.  We were under the impression the work orders were forgiven given the circumstances of neighborhood non-profits working together with the City on problem buildings.

However, and just recently, we learned the violation has been turned into a tax-lien against NEST, the current owner the building.  Is there any way you can work for us to get this resolved?  I am sure the City’s intentions is not to punish community organizations as they are working hard as volunteers to improve our neighborhoods.  As volunteers, I will admit that our efforts could be more professional at times, but volunteering and attempting to get things accomplished w/ COVID over the last 18 months has been really challenging.

I there any way you are able to assist NBA with this effort?  Please call w/ questions.  I am attaching the most pertinent pdf’s that have been sent on this issue for your reading pleasure.  Neither NEST nor the NBA has an extra $2,000 laying around to offset these fines.
Sincerely
Tim Jeckering
NBA president
